[{"id":30076,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/zo84HStC2WCKg55GKPFzK5WLpnpT587DKZXMathtnYo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/hFM1XpCwUlbSG4n1-3fKpqQSfDYPSL7VMik3AavoAlo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/z04qOKldxIs1tzE8WZcLOhNdFJBC0O_M4jq0V8UXxM0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Owgp4BQ0uv4Dv-fH3Rg0uaYGJ_5ew1MD3d9SPScRThI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":1,"solution":"In molecules (a), (c) and (d), the carbon atom has a multiple bond, only (b) has $\\mathrm{sp}^3$ hybridisation","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":29666,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A, B and C only","B, C and D only","C, D and E only","A, B and E only"],"answer":3,"solution":"A. Propanal ($CH_3CH_2CHO$) and propanone ($CH_3COCH_3$): Same formula $C_3H_6O$, different functional groups (aldehyde vs ketone) → Functional isomers. True <br>B. Ethoxyethane ($C_2H_5OC_2H_5$) and methoxypropane ($CH_3OC_3H_7$): Same ether group, different alkyl groups → Metamers. True <br>C. But-2-ene ($CH_3CH=CHCH_3$): No chiral carbon, shows geometrical isomerism (cis-trans), not optical. False <br>D. But-1-ene and but-2-ene: Both are alkenes, differ in position of double bond → Position isomers, not functional isomers. False <br>E. Pentane and 2,2-dimethylpropane: Both $C_5H_{12}$, different carbon skeleton → Chain isomers. True <br>Correct: A, B and E only.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29878,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9df40545-0ec2-4e3d-ac33-6925ed6be0e7-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 54px;\" /></p>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/21cec501-c5fe-4a11-970c-6e0d50613149-image.png\" />","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/001dd0eb-9b05-4f8d-81ff-7ceb02ff48a4-image.png\" style=\"width: 128px; height: 60px;\" />&nbsp;</p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/752d3d9f-51a4-4156-8607-778ba514c18b-image.png\" />&nbsp;</p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>In the dione, there are two keto groups are present. If&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#960;</mi></math>&nbsp;bonds are separated by a single bond, then we can say that there exists a conjugation. In the molecule&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/001dd0eb-9b05-4f8d-81ff-7ceb02ff48a4-image.png\" style=\"width: 128px; height: 60px;\" />&nbsp;all&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#960;</mi></math>&nbsp;bonds separated by single bonds and it is a dione.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29923,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A is false but R is true","Both A&nbsp;and R&nbsp;are true and R&nbsp;is the correct explanation of A","Both A&nbsp;and R&nbsp;are true but R&nbsp;is not the correct explanation of A","A is true but R&nbsp;is false"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Acetyl acetone in enol form have intramolecular H-bonding, which is absent in acetone.</p><p>enol form of&nbsp;Acetyl acetone is stabilised by conjugation and by&nbsp;intramolecular H-bonding.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bb6b81c5-2d5d-40a3-a9ee-f4c9b343cd98-image.png\" style=\"width: 290px; height: 84px;\" /></p><p>enol form of acetone is very less <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mo>&#60;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>%</mo></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4588e24d-3786-49f6-b9ab-6667b1732655-71becb32-8f6c-4d5a-8854-98871a69295b-image.png\" style=\"width: 521px; height: 145px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (16 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30070,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["only I and II are chiral compounds","only III i a chiral compound","only II and IV are chiral compounds","all four are chiral compounds"],"answer":0,"solution":"A chiral object or structure has four different groups attached to the carbocation.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":29749,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/FMx2MMVCVchY8-Dd6JY6fjBc9j_1G5H-uZH9OcpMT18.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29650,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false"],"answer":1,"solution":"Both statements are true.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29755,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are correct","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Aniline is a systematic name, whereas Aminobenzene is an IUPAC name.</p><p>Aniline, also known as aminobenzene or phenylamine, has <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math> carbon <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math> atoms, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>7</mn></math> hydrogen <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mfenced></math> atoms, and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> nitrogen <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></mfenced></math> atom in its chemical formula of <b><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math> or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></b>. Because aniline has an amino group in its structure, it is also an amine, hence it is classified as an aromatic amine. <br/><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/A0463.png\"/></p><p>Hence, the correct answer is B.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29987,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math><mo>(</mo><mtext>A</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>R</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>B</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>S</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>C</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>P</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>D</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>Q</mtext><mo>)</mo></math>","<math><mo>(</mo><mtext>A</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>P</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>B</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>S</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>C</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>R</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>D</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>Q</mtext><mo>)</mo></math>","<math><mo>(</mo><mtext>A</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>R</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>B</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>P</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>C</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>Q</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>D</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>S</mtext><mo>)</mo></math>","<math><mo>(</mo><mtext>A</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>R</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>B</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>P</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>C</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>S</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>D</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>Q</mtext><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<math><mo>(</mo><mtext>A</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>R</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>B</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>P</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>C</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>Q</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>D</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>S</mtext><mo>)</mo></math><br /><br />1. Coloured impurity <math> <mo>&#8594;</mo> </math> Charcoal treatment<br /><br />2. mixture of o &ndash; nitrophenol and p &ndash;nitrophenol<math> <mo>&#8594;</mo> </math>Steam distillation(Both form intermolecular H-Bond)<br /><br />3. Crude Naphtha<math> <mo>&#8594;</mo> </math>Fractional distillation<br /><br />4. mixture of glycerol and sugars <math> <mo>&#8594;</mo> </math> Distillation under reduced pressure","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30033,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Tollen's reagent","Molisch reagent","Neutral $\\mathrm{FeCl}_3$","Aqueous $\\mathrm{NaOH}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Phenol gives violet coloured comlex compound with neutral $\\mathrm{FeCl}_3$, benzoic acid gives pale dull yellow ppt. with neutral $\\mathrm{FeCl}_3$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2011","image":null},{"id":29989,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9a6312a3-5698-416f-854a-f1add4daef6d-image.png\" style=\"width: 174px; height: 109px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3e26cfcb-2aed-4131-922b-a3fa3b34c79a-image.png\" style=\"width: 104px; height: 109px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/80bf14c8-7247-4d75-b837-dba9d9dae6d8-image.png\" style=\"width: 155px; height: 109px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4a66f7c8-9a1c-4717-8a01-47e50de84d86-image.png\" style=\"width: 155px; height: 109px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"Kjeldahl method is not applicable to compounds containing nitrogen in nitro and azo groups and nitrogen present in the ring (e.g. pyridine) as nitrogen of these compounds does not change to ammonium sulphate under these conditions.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":29981,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CH</mi><msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi>CN</mi></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CHI</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CHBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CHCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Acidic character <math><mtext>&#945;</mtext></math> stability of conjugate base (anion)<br /><br />Stability of anion <math><mtext>&#945;</mtext><mo>-</mo><mi>M</mi></math> and <math><mo>&#8211;</mo><mi>I</mi></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow><mo>-</mo> <mi>M</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>I</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mtext>dominance</mtext></mrow> <mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow> </math><br /><br />Electron withdrawing groups increase acidic strength. Among the given compounds, the electron withdrawing strength of substituents</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/268e97ec-21e9-4729-a600-ce1744a3f10b-image.png\" style=\"width: 349px; height: 107px;\" /></p><p>In case of halogen&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;order of halogen&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cl</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math></p><p>Hence, <math><mi>C</mi><mi>H</mi><mtext>&#160;</mtext><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi><mi>N</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math> will be most acidic</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29703,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$q\\gt r\\gt p$","$r\\gt q\\gt p$","$q\\gt p\\gt r$","$\\mathrm{p}\\gt\\mathrm{q}\\gt\\mathrm{r}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"q is aromatic\nr is non-aromatic\np is antiaromatic\n$\\mathrm{q}>\\mathrm{r}>\\mathrm{p}$ (order of stability)\nAromatic > non-aromatic > antiaromatic","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (23 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29889,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7b49c81b-1a48-4b2e-9c0e-eed6a869e61a-image.png\" style=\"width: 282px; height: 178px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/03d62f67-9cd8-433d-affa-a1382b8a7897-image.png\" style=\"width: 282px; height: 135px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4ce7ecaf-8ab2-4b55-afc3-a36e1c82b2c8-image.png\" style=\"width: 325px; height: 139px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3131776e-2080-4465-a521-24ebcd261117-image.png\" style=\"width: 289px; height: 136px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"Halogenation of&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5b932104-b91a-4d7f-838b-b5c41b96c292-image.png\" style=\"width: 284px; height: 136px;\" />&nbsp;by electrophilic substitution reaction mechanism in presence of Lewis&nbsp;acid take place at meta position.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29818,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect.","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect","Both Statement I and Statement II are correct","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct."],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Sulphanilic acid is p-amino benzene sulphonic acid. It&nbsp;has no &ndash;COOH group hence no esterification test for carboxyl group.&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/087939aa-ed4c-46df-85ae-1a3ece4c1010-9896856.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 172px;\" /></p><p>But it has sulphur, and nitrogen atom hence gives red colour in Lassigne&#39;s test for extra element detection.</p><p>Hence, statement I is incorrect but statement II is correct.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29793,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c08331a2-3757-462d-8a5e-048623e944e6.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 145px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1e207d72-1b78-40c9-bb51-997c7ce628ee.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 148px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ff2ccf7d-7ea0-4c0d-81e1-9720f5b0b881.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 153px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3880ae41-8fdb-4990-982c-6bb86af3de69.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 119px;\"/>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Acidic hydrogen is a hydrogen atom in an acid that dissociates to generate a positive ion.</p><p>After removal of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>ion, the negative charge is formed. The more stable the negative charge, the more will be the acidic strength.</p><p>Due to cross conjugation of negative charge, it is<br/>most stabilised anion.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0605b598-81f8-49ea-bcaa-e76574a293c2.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 379px;\"/></p><p>Hence, the answer is option D.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29843,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>(A) Chloroform <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo></math> Aniline <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>III</mi></math>&nbsp;Distillation</p><p>(B) Benzoic acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo></math> Napthalene <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>IV</mi></math>&nbsp;Crystallisation</p><p>(C) Water <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo></math> Aniline <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;Steam distillation</p><p>(D) Napthalene <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo></math> Sodium chloride&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>II</mi></math>&nbsp;Sublimation</p><p>Aniline is purified using the process of steam distillation because aniline is steam volatile and it is insoluble in water.</p><p>Chloroform and aniline having boiling points <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>334</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>457</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math> can be separated by distillation. More volatile chloroform vaporizes first and is collected in the receiver. Aniline is left in the distillation flask.</p><p>Benzoic acid is soluble in hot water but naphthalene is not soluble, hence separation can be carried out by hot water crystallisation.</p><p>Naphthalene can also be separated by sublimation from non-volatile&nbsp;at room temperature.</p><p>The vapor of naphthalene can be collected and solidified.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30072,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["each forms equal number of isomers for a given compound","If in a compound one is present then so is the other","both are included in stereoisomerism","they have no similarity"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":29802,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["B, C and D only","A, B and C only","A, C and D only","A, B and D only"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f45709c4-81c6-4466-be73-19548618b72d.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 181px;\" /></p><p>Aromatic&nbsp;compounds are cyclic, planar and must obey Huckel&rsquo;s&nbsp;rule i.e. molecule must have <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></math> pi-electrons where n is an integer (i.e. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#8230;</mo></math>etc.).&nbsp; The compound B follws the Huckel&#39;s rule. The acid-base reactions fast reactions. Compound <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></math>, also called squaric acid is a strong acid. So, above reaction proceeds very fast. All <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math> bond lengths in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;are same due to resonance. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;shows tautomerism. A</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29648,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CH}_{2}=\\mathrm{CH}^{-}>\\mathrm{CH} \\equiv \\mathrm{C}^{-}>\\mathrm{CH}_{3}-\\mathrm{CH}_{2}^{-}$","$\\mathrm{CH} \\equiv \\mathrm{C}^{-}>\\mathrm{CH}_{2}=\\mathrm{CH}^{-}>\\mathrm{CH}_{3}-\\mathrm{CH}_{2}^{-}$","$\\mathrm{CH} \\equiv \\mathrm{C}^{-}>\\mathrm{CH}_{3}-\\mathrm{CH}_{2}^{-}>\\mathrm{CH}_{2}=\\mathrm{CH}^{-}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_{3}-\\mathrm{CH}_{2}^{-}>\\mathrm{CH}_{2}=\\mathrm{CH}^{-}>\\mathrm{CH} \\equiv \\mathrm{C}^{-}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Carbanion stability is determined by the s-character of the hybrid orbital bearing the negative charge.<br>The acetylide anion $CH \\equiv C^-$ has the carbanion on an sp hybridized carbon (50% s-character), providing optimal stabilization through efficient overlap with the charged orbital.<br>The vinyl anion $CH_2 = CH^-$ has the carbanion on an sp² hybridized carbon (33% s-character), offering moderate stabilization.<br>The primary alkyl anion $CH_3 - CH_2^-$ has the carbanion on an sp³ hybridized carbon (25% s-character), providing the least stabilization.<br>Greater s-character enables better penetration of the nucleus and enhanced stabilization of the negative charge.<br>Therefore, the order is $CH \\equiv C^- > CH_2 = CH^- > CH_3 - CH_2^-$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29823,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>A. Dicholoromethane&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>&nbsp;do not mix &amp; form two separate layers. So they can be separated by Differential solvent extraction.</p><p>B.&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3388b53d-1e9c-4f7e-8573-b4f24d0d235f-9896029_2.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 286px;\" /></p><p>Column chromatography is a technique in which the substances to be separated are introduced onto the top of a column packed with an adsorbent, passed through the column at different rates that depend on the affinity of each substance for the adsorbent and for the solvent or solvent mixture, and are usually collected in solution as they pass from the column at different times. Thus, the basic principle involved in column chromatography is to adsorb solutes of the solution with the help of a stationary phase and further separating the mixture into discrete components.</p><p>C. Kerosene / Naphthalene:&nbsp;Fractional Distillation, kerosene and naphthalene are different types of hydrocarbons that have different boiling points.</p><p>D.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>12</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>NaCl</mi></math>:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>12</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>NaCl</mi></math>&nbsp;are different compounds with different chemical and physical properties. As a result, they can be separated from each other by crystallisation.</p><p>So, the correct matching is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29939,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c4066aee-70f7-4cca-a940-42bae77e2540-image.png\" style=\"width: 138px; height: 109px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/47a55b26-efdf-4c53-a212-54db687da957-image.png\" style=\"width: 100px; height: 97px;\" />","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Cl</mi></math>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c5153895-28a1-4956-aa7e-c7ee7981c8cf-image.png\" style=\"width: 83px; height: 112px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"Due to conjugation of lone pair of chlorine with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></math>&nbsp;bond of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>, partial double bond character decrease bond length that&rsquo;s why&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo><mi>Cl</mi></math> have&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo><mi>Cl</mi></math>shortest bond length.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (04 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29853,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The equivalent of ammonia contains 14 grams of nitrogen. The number of equivalents of acid used is equal to number of equivalents of ammonia evolved.</p><p>Number of equivalents of acid used&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>Normality</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>Volume</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>in</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></math></p><p>Hence, the percentage of nitrogen can be calculated form the following&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mfenced><mrow><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></mrow><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>organic</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>compound</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>56</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29771,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["(A) is true but (R) is false","Both (A) and (R) are true but (R) is not the correct explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>","(A) is false but (R) is true","Both (A) and (R) are true and (R) is the correct explanation of (A)"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Allylic halides: These are the compounds where the halogen group is attached to a <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math> hybridised carbon atom next to the carbon which is already in a double bond with another carbon atom.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b3291ea8-0600-4841-8cc2-305221d0a643.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 100px;\"/></p><p>Hence, the answer is option A.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29739,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["4 and 1","5 and 2","3 and 1","5 and 1"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/WeSZemqeToPUJ4WQZ4tNUTjQkNMnI4B4V0-O5dQNM1I.original.fullsize.png\"><br />it has $5 \\sigma$ bonds and $1 \\pi$ bond.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29942,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/27264322-f070-486c-88f5-0710a40486e6-image.png\" style=\"width: 149px; height: 85px;\" />","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#8801;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bee52e07-cfa7-4d24-84d1-80d6550d9fcb-image.png\" style=\"width: 128px; height: 75px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/91f101b8-d33d-4928-8154-739535bcb98a-image.png\" style=\"width: 205px; height: 127px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/41a0f286-7af6-4a63-b6fd-05dbac34f737-image.png\" style=\"width: 340px; height: 123px;\" />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (03 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29898,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi>Cl</mi></msub></math> in compound <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi>AgCl</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3849</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>107</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>87</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>35</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>mol</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo></math> mass of chlorine <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi>Cl</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>35</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0953</mn><mi>gm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>%</mo></math> wt. of chlorine <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0953</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>19</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>06</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29840,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Let the mass of organic compound = m g</p><p>Volume of nitrogen collected = V<sub>1 </sub>mL</p><p>Room temperature = T<sub>1</sub>K</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>78</mn><mi>ml</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>280</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi>total</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>759</mn><mi>mmHg</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msub></math>= Atmospheric pressure &ndash; Aqueous tension</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>759</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>744</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mi>mmHg</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>22400</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>at</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>STP</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>weighs</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>28</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>.</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gas</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>at</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>STP</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>weighs</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>28</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></mrow><mn>22400</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi>z</mi></msub></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>744</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>78</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>760</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>082</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>280</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>00097</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mi>Nitrogen</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02716</mn></math>g</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02716</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>125</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>21</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>728</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 2)","image":null}]